data.current_description:
Creates a payment session for [Drop-in](https://docs.adyen.com/online-payments/build-your-integration/sessions-flow/?platform=Web&integration=Drop-in), [Components](https://docs.adyen.com/online-payments/build-your-integration/sessions-flow/?platform=Web&integration=Components), and [Hosted Checkout](https://docs.adyen.com/online-payments/build-your-integration/sessions-flow/?platform=Web&integration=Hosted+Checkout) integrations.

The response contains encrypted payment session data. The front end then uses the session data to make any required server-side calls for the payment flow.

You get the payment outcome asynchronously, in an [AUTHORISATION](https://docs.adyen.com/api-explorer/#/Webhooks/latest/post/AUTHORISATION) webhook.
data.summary_suggestion: Create encrypted payment session for checkout
data.description_suggestion: Creates an encrypted payment session for Drop-in, Components, and Hosted Checkout integrations. The session data is returned in the response and must be passed to the front end to initialize the payment flow. The session enables secure client-side payment processing. Payment authorization results are delivered asynchronously via AUTHORISATION webhook. Requires authentication via API key.
data.reasoning: Original description lacks clarity on what the encrypted session data is used for and doesn't explicitly state the asynchronous nature of payment outcomes. Added context about session initialization, security model, webhook delivery mechanism, and authentication requirement to improve AI agent understanding of when and how to use this operation.

Use this operation to poll for asynchronous payment results after session creation.

data.current_summary: Create a token to store payment details
data.current_description: Creates a token to store the shopper's payment details. This token can be used for the shopper's future payments.
data.summary_suggestion: Tokenize and store shopper payment method
data.description_suggestion: Creates a reusable token for storing the shopper's payment method details securely. The token enables recurring or one-click payments without requiring the shopper to re-enter payment information. Requires the shopper's payment details in the request. Returns a unique token identifier that can be referenced in future payment requests. The stored payment method is associated with the shopper's account for future transactions.

data.current_description:
This operation takes the origin domains and returns a JSON object containing the corresponding origin keys for the domains. 
> If you're still using origin key for your Web Drop-in or Components integration, we recommend [switching to client key](https://docs.adyen.com/development-resources/client-side-authentication/migrate-from-origin-key-to-client-key). This allows you to use a single key for all origins, add or remove origins without generating a new key, and detect the card type from the number entered in your payment form.
data.summary_suggestion: Generate origin keys for specified domains
data.description_suggestion: Generates origin keys for the provided origin domains, returning a JSON object mapping each domain to its corresponding origin key. This operation is used for Web Drop-in or Components integration authentication. Note: Adyen recommends migrating to client key for improved flexibility (single key for all origins, dynamic origin management, and card type detection).

data.current_description:
Sends payment parameters (like amount, country, and currency) together with other required input details collected from the shopper. To know more about required parameters for specific payment methods, refer to our [payment method guides](https://docs.adyen.com/payment-methods). 
The response depends on the [payment flow](https://docs.adyen.com/payment-methods#payment-flow):
 * For a direct flow, the response includes a `pspReference` and a `resultCode` with the payment result, for example **Authorised** or **Refused**. 
* For a redirect or additional action, the response contains an `action` object.
data.description_suggestion: Authorizes a payment transaction by sending payment parameters (amount, country, currency) and shopper details. The response varies by payment flow: direct authorizations return `pspReference` and `resultCode` (e.g., Authorised, Refused); redirect or additional action flows return an `action` object requiring further processing. Side effects: Creates a payment record and may trigger 3D Secure or other authentication flows.

data.current_summary: Get the brands and other details of a card
data.current_description:
Use this endpoint to get information about the card or network token that enables you to decideon the routing of the transaction and the eligibility of the card for the type of transaction.

If you include [your supported brands](https://docs.adyen.com/api-explorer/#/CheckoutService/latest/post/cardDetails__reqParam_supportedBrands) in the request, the response also tells you if you support each [brand that was identified on the card](https://docs.adyen.com/api-explorer/#/CheckoutService/latest/post/cardDetails__resParam_details).
 
If you have an API-only integration and collect card data, use this endpoint to find out if the shopper's card is co-branded. For co-branded cards, you must let the shopper choose the brand to pay with  if you support both brands.
data.summary_suggestion: Retrieve card brand and co-brand details
data.description_suggestion: Retrieves card or network token information including brand identification and co-brand detection. Accepts card data and optional list of supported brands. Returns identified card brands, co-brand status, and whether each identified brand is supported by your integration. Use this endpoint to determine transaction routing eligibility and to prompt shoppers to select a brand for co-branded cards. Supports API-only integrations with card data collection.
